dismissalComment.html: short, pulled, top-edged, gone! The end of a triumphant innings from Roy, the MCG rises as one to a brilliant performance. A bit of a tired ending, went for the big humpty over the leg side, but ended up with a lobbed chance to backward square. But what a statement innings from a resurgent one-day team!

commentTextItems.html: battered through long-on, and England win by five wickets!

commentPostTextItems.html: 10.25pm So, that sums things up from the first ODI. Have a read of Dan Brettig's match report before you go, and we'll see you at the Gabba for Match 2 out of 5 in what promises to be a high-octane ODI series.

10.20pm Time for some presentations. First up, Australia's skipper. "He didn't give us a chance, and he chanced his arm," says Steve Smith of an awesome Jason Roy innings. "They got off to an absolute flyer and we couldn't pull them back."

Unsurprisingly, Jason Roy is man of the match. "Incredibly special, I don't have too many words right now. Halesy was pretty disappointed [to lose his England ODI highest score]. It had been a tough season last season, so to be selected was incredibly special.
"I was so happy, first time here, what an incredlble place," he says of the MCG. And his hand is "okay", he says...

10.15pm Ben: "Yet again Root fails to convert. When will England selectors come to their senses? " I know... shocking... Still, a tremendous supporting hand from England's back-to-the-ranks No.4, who has reaffirmed his class across formats
"He's imposing at the crease, and what a way to start the series," says England's captain, Eoin Morgan. "It sums up the character of the bloke, coming back in."
"Australia are a strong side and will come back incredibly hard at Brisbane, but it's a nice way to start the series."

10.11pm England win with seven balls to spare on a memorable night at the MCG. A record innings, a first-ever chase of a 300-plus total by any side at Australia's grandest ground, and a vital calling-card from a one-day squad that has high expectations, and plenty of English pride to salvage

Dan: "Well, they are bottling it. Obviously they are in such a dominant position that they will win, but as an earlier commenter said, it's not a good sign for their bigger picture." That earlier commentator now accuses me of spinning his words like an American politician, but seeing as another naysayer has now endorsed his words, he clearly speaks for an unhinged demographic. Much like another American politician...

commentTextItems.html: a yawning mow from Mo! Lucky not to lose his poles. Careful now
a bottom-handed bunt down to long-on, and the scores are level
dabbed into the gap for a single
nicely flighted, into the blockhole
drilled hard to cover. Another dot...

commentPostTextItems.html: England need three from 12 balls, with five wickets in hand. In case you were under the impression they were bottling it...

headshotImage.caption: Marcus Stoinis player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Marcus Stoinis player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Jos Buttler c Starc b Stoinis 4 (10b 0x4 0x6 15m) SR: 40

commentTextItems.html: launched into the leg side for the winning runs ... but no! It's a top-edge to deep midwicket!

commentPostTextItems.html: Well, that was a torrid innings for Buttler. He seemed to attract all of the Aussie aggression. But hard to see how it can make a difference to the final result...

commentTextItems.html: outside off, dabbed into the off side for another sharp single
on the toes, that could have been it, but Finch at short midwicket wears the shot on his shin. Ouch
in the arc, and tonked over the bowler to bring England to within a solitary boundary
cracked straight to cover

commentPostTextItems.html: Chris: "Here again proof why England will never be number side in any format, this game should been done by now. But No, not with England, they'll go back to the tried and true nature of the English cricketer and dink and donk alongand then all of a sudden they run rate creeps up, which in effect makes the English cricketer panic and lose his wicket and then for the supporter it's the all to familiar stressful ending yet again." Are you seriously saying that a national-record innings and a highest run-chase at the MCG isn't good enough for you? Some people...

commentTextItems.html: short and sharp again, Australia defending this match with aggression and tenacity, but they are already several fathoms underwater

headshotImage.caption: Andrew Tye player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Andrew Tye player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: short and through to the keeper

commentPostTextItems.html: Daniel: "Roy bats at 5/6 in first class cricket. Its a number 1 and 3 England are lacking. His technique against the swinging ball is poor so he can't bat higher."

commentTextItems.html: short and aggressive, targetting the head, but pulled down to backward square to keep the runs ticking
fuller length, picks the gap this time with a thumping drive, splitting the covers, and handing the strike back to the more settled Root
lifting into the gloves, that's a sharp delivery, keeping England honest

commentPostTextItems.html: jacob: "Now they seem to be drawing out the game. I'll laugh like a drain if they stuff this chase up now like they are doing." It'll take an incredible stuff-up from here. Just saying...

commentTextItems.html: another single, chipping the deficit away
slower ball again, swings late, met with a compact drive to cover

commentPostTextItems.html: Mark: "The counter-argument to what people are saying (sensibly) about Roy is David Warner. Made his international debut in T20 before his FC debut, but turned into a very fine Test batsman." Damn right. He is living proof that the classiest players find a way, whatever their heritage

commentTextItems.html: outswinging slower-ball yorker. Not a bad nut to produce at the best of times. Beats Root all ends up outside off
thumped to the leg side

dismissalComment.html: he's got Smith! What a strike for Rashid. Gets it outside off, just a hint of turn, and a thin nick to Buttler. He actually played outside this, away from his body, and got an inside edge. Not sure Buttler took it entirely cleanly, but it stayed in

dismissalText.commentary: Travis Head b Plunkett 5 (8b 1x4 0x6 14m) SR: 62.5

dismissalComment.html: dragged on! We saw a few of those in the Test match here. Good length, outside off, aiming to play square through the off side and gets a bottom edge into the timber. The seventh ball of the over proves a bonus for England!

headshotImage.caption: Jonny Bairstow player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Jonny Bairstow player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Aaron Finch c Bairstow b Ali 107 (119b 10x4 3x6 138m) SR: 89.91

dismissalComment.html: picks out deep midwicket! Stands still this time, opts for the leg side, heaves across the line and clubs it down the throat of Bairstow

headshotImage.caption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Mitchell Marsh b Rashid 50 (68b 2x4 2x6 89m) SR: 73.52

dismissalComment.html: through him! Nicely done from Rashid. Another one that goes straight on, Marsh giving himself a touch of room, misses the drive and the ball tickles leg stump

dismissalText.commentary: Marcus Stoinis c Root b Woakes 60 (40b 5x4 2x6 55m) SR: 150

dismissalComment.html: finds mid-off! Back of a length, aiming to club it down the ground, doesn't get the elevation and Root grabs it coming forward

dismissalText.commentary: Tim Paine c Ali b Plunkett 27 (31b 3x4 0x6 56m) SR: 87.09

dismissalComment.html: well judged on the rope! As calm as you like from Moeen. A short ball, goes for the pull, gets a top edge, Moeen, at deep backward square, is in the shadows which are starting to come across the ground but knows exactly where the rope is and pouches the catch

headshotImage.longCaption: Jason Roy player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Pat Cummins c Roy b Plunkett 12 (10b 1x4 0x6 14m) SR: 120

dismissalComment.html: this is a long way up...and taken at long on. Jason Roy runs in, steadies himself, and makes no mistake. Cummins aiming to clear the leg side, got too much height and not enough distance

headshotImage.longCaption: Jhye Richardson player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Jason Roy c sub (JA Richardson) b Starc 180 (151b 16x4 5x6 151m) SR: 119.2

dismissalComment.html: short, pulled, top-edged, gone! The end of a triumphant innings from Roy, the MCG rises as one to a brilliant performance. A bit of a tired ending, went for the big humpty over the leg side, but ended up with a lobbed chance to backward square. But what a statement innings from a resurgent one-day team!

dismissalText.commentary: Jonny Bairstow c †Paine b Starc 14 (11b 2x4 0x6 22m) SR: 127.27

dismissalComment.html: edged and gone! A tame end for Bairstow - good line outside off, extra bounce, and a loose tickle through to the keeper. Very Vince in the Ashes, that dismissal

headshotImage.caption: Marcus Stoinis player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Marcus Stoinis player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Alex Hales c Stoinis b Cummins 4 (3b 1x4 0x6 6m) SR: 133.33

dismissalComment.html: short, and a miscued pull, as Hales ducked into his pull as he realised he'd been beaten for pace. A simple catch pops up to short midwicket, and Australia are very much in the hunt now...

dismissalText.commentary: Joe Root not out 91 (110b 5x4 0x6 186m) SR: 82.72
Eoin Morgan c Smith b Cummins 1 (4b 0x4 0x6 11m) SR: 25

dismissalComment.html: short, wide, and carved to point! Oops! Is this England's late dose of the wobbles? Probably too little too late, but you never rightly know...
